Thus, for each agent i, there is a value function σi : Rni → R. In particular, Raiffa [17] shows how to systematically  construct an additive value function to each party involved in a negotiation.
Assuming that money transfer between agents is possible , the set Att then contains three attributes : • T , taking values from the set { 0 , 1 } , indicates whether the task T is assigned to agent B ; • R , taking values from the set of non-negative integer , indicates the amount of resource R being allocated to agent B ; 